`/{{PREFIX}}` pipeline pushes commits to remote via the **`GITHUB_TOKEN`** environment variable.

**Where it's configured:** `~/.claude/settings.json` (user-global settings). Env var is available on all platforms (Linux, macOS, Windows under Git Bash) — picked up by every Bash invocation in the pipeline.

**Where it's used:** the `/{{PREFIX}}` orchestrator, Step 5 (`--feature`) and Step 4 (`--bugfix`). Script:

```bash
remote_path=$(git remote get-url origin | sed -e 's#^https://[^/]*@#https://#' -e 's#^https://##')
git push "https://x-access-token:${GITHUB_TOKEN}@${remote_path}" HEAD
```

The sed filter strips any existing `https://user@` prefix and the `https://` scheme, leaving `github.com/owner/repo`. Then the URL is reassembled with `x-access-token`. This lets the pipeline reuse whatever `origin` is configured, without hardcoding the URL per project.

**If push doesn't work:**

- Check `echo $GITHUB_TOKEN` via Bash — empty means the env var isn't being set
- Check the token's scope on GitHub: need `repo` (for private) or `public_repo` (for public)
- On Windows, verify `settings.json` uses the right key (`env` / `environmentVariables` — depends on Claude Code version)

The script continues the pipeline without blocking if push fails — this is by design (see `/{{PREFIX}}.md`: "If push fails → show error to user and continue without blocking").

Related: [[cross-platform-bash]] (push is Bash-only).
